opotkin, Pierre Clastres, James Scott, Fernand Braudel and Imanuel Wallerstein, this study examines the full historical and contemporary possibilities for establishing self-governing communities at the edges of the capitalist world-system, considering the historical forces that often militate against those who try to practice mutual aid in the face of state power and capitalist incursion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCapitalismxMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 0aDon CossacksxSocial networkszRussia (Federation)zDon River Region. 0aExilesxSocial networksvCase studies. 0aIndians of MexicoxSocial networkszMexicozChiapas. 0aPrisonersxSocial networks. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  acapitalism critique.  acapitalism.  acapitalist refugee.  achiapas zapatistas.  acossacks on the don river.  acossacks.  adon river cossacks.  adon river region.  aescaping capitalism.  aexile from capitalism.  aexile in prison.  aexiled in prison.  aexilic communities.  aforced exile.  ahistory of self governing communities.  aliving in exile.  along term prisoners.  amexican indians.  amexican zapatistas.  amoral effects of capitalism.  apenal exile.  azapatistas.1 aO'Hearn, Denis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028729740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096248440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962484/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY